At least, the sum of $7,000 was splashed on four different filmmakers across Africa at the AMAA and STarTimes’ online short film festival, The Shorts. The winners of the festival emerged from Nigeria, Uganda, and Ghana after their short films had been judged by a panel of established filmmakers. Ugandan filmmaker Edmond Tamale’s ‘Ateker’ won the award for Best Documentary and a cash prize of $1000. Nigeria’s Frank Abasiekong also won the sum of $1000 and a Tecno Camon phone for his crime short film entitled Room 10. Ghana’s Frank Dzikunu emerged second with an animation entitled Sad story of Kojo. Dzikunu also won a Tecno Camon and a sum of $2000 while the winner of the festival award, Enobong Nkanta walked away with the sum of $3,000 alongside a brand new Lenovo laptop. She won the competition with her short film entitled Mama’s Song.   Shon Nerat aims at causing ripples with Afro Electro Vibe     film trainees graduate from Kunle Afolayan’s KAP Academy     Emmanuela, Mark Angel join Broda Shaggi as ambassadors for…   Present at the finale were Femi Odugbemi, Peace Anyiam-Osigwe, Tunde Kelani, Lucy Liu, Femi Adebayo, and Alex Jian. Speaking at the event, Anyiam-Osigwe, Kelani reiterated the essence of short films and the need for the industry to support young filmmakers trying to find their voices through short films. StarTimes Nigeria head, Alex Jian was thankful for the creatives that supported the festival and promised to ensure his brand continues to support The Shorts every year. He said the move is to ensure StarTimes adds its quota to the growth of indigenous creatives in Nigeria and across Africa.